##############

When using a logic analyzer on the Game Boy its cartridge connector, you
see that the upper address lines (A14-A8) will go low after reading from
the cartridge. The lower address lines (A7-A0) will keep their value
however. This is odd, because according to the schematics all address
lines (A14-A0) are treated the same: The CPU sets them to 0 at the end
of a memory access. The behaviour we see on the logic analyzer results
from the lower address lines being roughly double the length than the
upper ones. So they have roughly double the delay until they settle on a
new value. This additional delay causes the 1-to-0 change to arrive too
late, after the ADDR_LATCH signal goes low, so the lower address lines
will get held by the latch as they were during the memory access.

Check for this in GTKWave:
 * Address at cartridge bus must be 0x80ff at primary marker.

##############
